==> Trivia Game FilesAll Trivia Game Files must be created in a specific format. All informationfor each question must be on the same line. The format is...[CATEGORY] QUESTION|ANSWERAn example question would be...[GEOGRAPHY] What is the capital of France?|ParisThe category is optional. You may leave it off all together. But if you'regoing to use it, it must be at the start of the line and contained in []'s.You can also embed CR's in your questions with the \ symbol. If you want ablank line (2 CR's), then just use two \'s.==> Running the FERunning the FE software is pretty easy. For best results, run the TriviaFE DIRECTLY from DOS, not within any other terminal software or shells.To load the FE, type TRIVIA C:\DIRECTORY\GAMEFILE.DAT. So if you wantedto run the FE with the game file GAME.DAT that was located in directoryGAMEFILE, you would type TRIVIA C:\GAMEFILE\GAME.DAT. If the name of yourgame file is TRIVIA.DAT and it is located in the same directory as theFE software, then you you can just type TRIVIA, as the game file will beloaded automatically.Your modem must be in COMPORT 1 or 2. Once you're in the terminal, pressALT+H for the help screen. Below are a list of commonly used functions...ALT+N	Sets your name as the HostALT+G   Begins/Ends a Trivia gameALT+C   Toggles Carry Over modeALT+L   Loads a questionALT+B   Begins a roundALT+S   Displays scoresALT+U   Allows you to update player scoresALT+Q   Quits the terminalALT+Z   Hangs up the modemALT+X   Shells to DOS==> TRIVMIX.EXEI wrote the TRIVMIX.EXE program to help me "shuffle" my game files.I usually create my game files and write each category one at a time.So I'll have all my GEOGRAPHY questions first, then HISTORY, then ART& LIT,etc. And I usually have 5 categories with 10 questions. So to shufflethe file, I type TRIVMIX <FILENAME> <# OF QUESTIONS>/<# OF CATEGORIES>.If you're going to use TRIVMIX, you MUST have the same number of questionsin each category. So if you were going to shuffle TRIVIA.DAT that has 5categories with 10 questions in each, you would type...TRIVMIX TRIVIA.DAT 10/5I suggest having a BACKUP copy of your game file before using TRIVMIX onit. I usually have one extended with .DAT and one with .BAK.==> Any questions?Just email me if you have any questions.